title: Question 6
prompt: The President’s veto power is an example of:
description:
Click the one best answer to each question.

The excerpt from the Constitution of the United States gives the President the power to veto, or refuse, any law passed by Congress. However, the law can still be passed if two-thirds of Congress votes for it.
feedback: The system of checks and balances in the United States constitution gives the branches of the United States government (Congress, the President and the Supreme Court) powers over each other. The President’s veto power is a power over the Congress, since the President can refuse a law passed by Congress.
